                    <dt>
                        <a href="#accordion2" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="accordion2"
                            class="accordion-title accordionTitle js-accordionTrigger">
                            Cooking Terminology</a>
                    </dt>
                    <dd class="accordion-content accordionItem is-collapsed" id="accordion2" aria-hidden="true">
                        <p>
                            <ul>
                                <li><b>Sauté:</b><br>
                                    To cook food quickly in a small amount of oil or fat over high heat, often stirring continuously. This method is used to lightly brown food while preserving its texture.
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <b>Braise:</b><br>
                                    A cooking technique that involves browning meat or vegetables in fat, then slowly cooking them in a covered pot with a small amount of liquid at low heat. This method results in tender and flavorful dishes.
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <b>Blanch:</b><br>
                                    Briefly immersing vegetables or fruits in boiling water, then quickly transferring them to ice-cold water to halt the cooking process. Blanching helps retain color, texture, and nutrients.
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <b>Deglaze:</b><br>
                                    Adding liquid (such as wine, broth, or vinegar) to a hot pan to loosen and dissolve browned bits of food stuck to the bottom after sautéing or searing. This process adds flavor to sauces or gravies.
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <b>Simmer:</b><br>
                                    Cooking food gently over low heat, keeping the liquid just below boiling. It's a slow-cooking method that allows flavors to meld while preventing the food from boiling vigorously.
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <b>Grill vs. Broil:</b><br>
                                    Grilling involves cooking food over direct heat, while broiling involves cooking food under high heat from above. Both methods produce a charred or caramelized exterior while keeping the interior moist.
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <b>Marinate:</b><br>
                                    Soaking food (usually meat or vegetables) in a seasoned liquid mixture, known as a marinade, to enhance flavor, tenderize, and sometimes preserve it before cooking.
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <b>Fold:</b><br>
                                    Gently combining ingredients using a spatula in a lifting and turning motion, ensuring delicate mixtures (like whipped cream or egg whites) are evenly incorporated without deflating them.
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <b>Reduce:</b><br>
                                    Boiling a liquid to evaporate water, concentrating flavors and thickening the consistency. This technique is used to create sauces or syrups with intensified taste.
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <b>Zest:</b><br>
                                    The outer colored part of citrus fruit peel, often grated or peeled off and used to add citrus flavor to dishes without the bitterness of the white pith.
                                </li>
                            </ul>
                        </p>
                    </dd>
                    <dt>
                        <a href="#accordion3" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="accordion3"
                            class="accordion-title accordionTitle js-accordionTrigger">
                            Cooking Mistakes to Avoid:
                        </a>
                    </dt>
                    <dd class="accordion-content accordionItem is-collapsed" id="accordion3" aria-hidden="true">
                        <p>
                            <ul>
                                <li><b>Overcrowding the Pan:</b><br>
                                    Avoid placing too many ingredients in a small cooking space as it can lead to uneven cooking. Overcrowding prevents proper heat circulation, resulting in steaming instead of browning.
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <b>Skipping Preheating the Pan:</b><br>
                                    Always preheat your pan before adding ingredients. Skipping this step can affect the cooking time and texture of the food, causing it to stick or cook unevenly.
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <b>Ignoring Knife Sharpness:</b><br>
                                    Using a dull knife can be unsafe and lead to uneven cuts. Maintain a sharp knife for precise cutting and reduce the risk of accidents in the kitchen.
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <b>Not Tasting as You Cook:</b><br>
                                    Failing to taste your food as you cook can result in under-seasoned or over-seasoned dishes. Regular tasting allows for adjustments to achieve the desired flavor profile.
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <b>Skipping Resting Time for Meat: </b><br>
                                    Allow cooked meat to rest before slicing to retain juices evenly throughout the dish. Cutting meat immediately after cooking can cause moisture loss, resulting in dry meat.
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <b>Using Incorrect Measurements:</b><br>
                                    Accurate measurements are crucial in cooking. Using the wrong measurements, especially in baking, can significantly alter the texture and taste of the final dish.
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <b>Neglecting Oven Calibration:</b><br>
                                    An improperly calibrated oven can lead to uneven baking or cooking temperatures. Use an oven thermometer to ensure accurate temperature settings.
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <b>Ignoring Recipe Instructions:</b><br>
                                    Follow recipes closely, especially for new dishes. Ignoring or altering essential steps may affect the overall outcome of the dish.
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <b>Not Letting Ingredients Reach Room Temperature:</b><br>
                                    Some recipes require ingredients to be at room temperature. Neglecting this step can affect the texture and consistency of the final product.
                                </li>
                                <li>
                                    <b>Overlooking Organization and Preparation:</b><br>
                                    Lack of organization and preparation ('mise en place') can lead to chaos while cooking. Prepare ingredients beforehand to streamline the cooking process and avoid mistakes.
                                </li>
                            </ul>
                        </p>
